---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Frequently Asked Questions About Taiwan" description="Answers to the most commonly asked questions about Taiwan — geography, culture, economy, democracy, safety, bubble tea, TSMC, and more. Your comprehensive Taiwan FAQ." lang="en">
  <div class="faq-page">

    <!-- Hero Banner -->
    <section class="faq-hero">
      <div class="hero-inner">
        <h1>Frequently Asked Questions About Taiwan</h1>
        <p class="hero-subtitle">Everything you want to know about this remarkable island — from basic facts to culture, economy, and society.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- FAQ Content -->
    <section class="faq-content">
      <div class="faq-inner">

        <!-- Section: Basic Facts -->
        <div class="faq-section">
          <h2 class="faq-section-title">Basic Facts</h2>

          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary>What is Taiwan?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>Taiwan is an island located in East Asia, off the southeastern coast of mainland China, with a population of approximately 23 million people. It is officially known as the Republic of China (ROC) and features a vibrant democracy, a high-tech economy, and a rich cultural heritage shaped by Indigenous, Chinese, Japanese, and Western influences. Taiwan is renowned for its semiconductor industry, night markets, and universal healthcare system.</p>
              <a href="/en/history/prehistoric-era-and-indigenous-peoples" class="read-more">Learn more about Taiwan's origins &rarr;</a>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary>Is Taiwan a country?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>Taiwan functions as an independent sovereign state with its own government, military, currency (New Taiwan Dollar), passport, and democratic elections. However, its international status is complex due to the People's Republic of China's "One China" claim. Taiwan is not a member of the United Nations, though it maintains unofficial diplomatic relations with many countries and is a major global economic player.</p>
              <a href="/en/society/democratic-system" class="read-more">Explore Taiwan's democratic system &rarr;</a>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary>Where is Taiwan located?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>Taiwan is located in the western Pacific Ocean, about 180 kilometers (112 miles) off the southeastern coast of China, separated by the Taiwan Strait. It sits at the junction of the East China Sea and the South China Sea. The island is roughly the size of the Netherlands, spanning about 394 km from north to south, with a dramatic landscape that includes over 200 mountain peaks above 3,000 meters.</p>
              <a href="/en/geography/outlying-islands" class="read-more">Discover Taiwan's geography &rarr;</a>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary>What language do they speak in Taiwan?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>The official language is Mandarin Chinese (Traditional characters), but Taiwan is a multilingual society. Taiwanese Hokkien (commonly called "Taiwanese") is widely spoken, especially in the south. Hakka is spoken by the Hakka community, and there are 16 officially recognized Indigenous languages belonging to the Austronesian language family. English education is widespread, and many younger Taiwanese speak conversational English.</p>
              <a href="/en/culture/indigenous-cultures" class="read-more">Learn about Taiwan's indigenous cultures &rarr;</a>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary>Is Taiwan safe to visit?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>Taiwan is widely considered one of the safest destinations in Asia and the world. It consistently ranks highly in global safety indexes, with low crime rates, excellent public infrastructure, and a welcoming attitude toward tourists. The public transportation system is clean and efficient, convenience stores are open 24/7 everywhere, and the universal healthcare system is accessible to visitors. Natural hazards such as typhoons and earthquakes do occur, but Taiwan has robust early-warning and preparedness systems.</p>
              <a href="/en/lifestyle/convenience-store-culture" class="read-more">Discover Taiwan's convenience culture &rarr;</a>
            </div>
          </details>
        </div>

        <!-- Section: Culture & Tourism -->
        <div class="faq-section">
          <h2 class="faq-section-title">Culture & Tourism</h2>

          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary>What is Taiwan known for?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>Taiwan is known for many things: its world-leading semiconductor industry (TSMC), bubble tea, vibrant night markets, scenic mountain landscapes, hot springs, and a thriving democracy. Culturally, Taiwan is celebrated for its temple festivals, Indigenous heritage, contemporary art scene, and pop music (Mandopop). It's also famous for its friendly people, incredible food diversity, and the unique blend of traditional and modern that defines everyday life on the island.</p>
              <a href="/en/culture/traditional-festivals" class="read-more">Explore Taiwan's cultural festivals &rarr;</a>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary>What is "Taiwan Sensibility" (台灣感性)?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>"Taiwan Sensibility" refers to a cultural aesthetic and emotional quality that is distinctly Taiwanese — a blend of warmth, nostalgia, resilience, and creative energy. It manifests in everything from retro street scenes and hand-lettered shop signs to the island's unique approach to design, food presentation, and community life. This sensibility has gained international recognition, particularly in Korean and Japanese pop culture circles, where Taiwan's laid-back charm and photogenic streetscapes have become a cultural export.</p>
              <a href="/en/culture/temple-culture-and-religion" class="read-more">Discover Taiwan's cultural soul &rarr;</a>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary>What are the best night markets in Taiwan?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>Taiwan's night markets are a cornerstone of local culture and a must-visit for any traveler. The most famous include Shilin Night Market and Raohe Street Night Market in Taipei, Fengjia Night Market in Taichung (one of the largest in Taiwan), Liuhe Night Market in Kaohsiung, and Tainan's Garden Night Market. Each market has its own character and signature dishes, from stinky tofu and oyster omelets to pepper buns and grilled squid.</p>
              <a href="/en/food/night-market-culture" class="read-more">Dive into night market culture &rarr;</a>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary>What is bubble tea and where did it originate?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>Bubble tea (also known as boba tea or pearl milk tea) is a tea-based drink invented in Taiwan in the 1980s, featuring chewy tapioca pearls at the bottom. It was created in Taichung, with both Chun Shui Tang and Hanlin Tea Room claiming to be the originators. Bubble tea has since become a global phenomenon, with countless variations including fruit teas, cheese-foam teas, and brown sugar milk tea. It is one of Taiwan's most successful cultural exports.</p>
              <a href="/en/food/bubble-tea" class="read-more">Read the full story of bubble tea &rarr;</a>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary>What are the must-visit places in Taiwan?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>Top destinations include Taipei (the capital, home to Taipei 101 and the National Palace Museum), Taroko Gorge (a stunning marble canyon in Hualien), Sun Moon Lake (a serene alpine lake), Alishan (famous for its sunrise and forest railways), Jiufen (a charming mountain town), and Kenting National Park (tropical beaches in the south). Taiwan's hot springs, particularly in Beitou and Wulai, and the dramatic scenery of the East Coast are also highlights.</p>
              <a href="/en/nature/national-parks" class="read-more">Explore Taiwan's national parks &rarr;</a>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary>What is Taiwanese food like?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>Taiwanese cuisine is a rich fusion of Hokkien, Hakka, Japanese, Indigenous, and mainland Chinese culinary traditions. Staple dishes include beef noodle soup, braised pork rice (lu rou fan), oyster omelets, scallion pancakes, and xiao long bao (soup dumplings). Street food culture is central to daily life, with an emphasis on fresh, affordable, and flavorful meals. Taiwan is also renowned for its tea culture, tropical fruits, and innovative desserts.</p>
              <a href="/en/food/taiwanese-street-food" class="read-more">Discover Taiwan's street food &rarr;</a>
            </div>
          </details>
        </div>

        <!-- Section: Economy & Technology -->
        <div class="faq-section">
          <h2 class="faq-section-title">Economy & Technology</h2>

          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary>Why is TSMC important?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>TSMC (Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company) is the world's largest and most advanced contract chipmaker, producing over 90% of the world's most advanced semiconductors. Founded by Morris Chang in 1987, TSMC manufactures chips for major companies including Apple, NVIDIA, AMD, and Qualcomm. Its dominance in cutting-edge chip fabrication makes Taiwan a critical node in the global technology supply chain, often described as the "Silicon Shield" that enhances Taiwan's geopolitical significance.</p>
              <a href="/en/technology/semiconductor-industry" class="read-more">Learn about Taiwan's semiconductor industry &rarr;</a>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary>What is the "Silicon Shield"?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>The "Silicon Shield" is a geopolitical concept suggesting that Taiwan's dominance in semiconductor manufacturing — particularly through TSMC — acts as a form of strategic deterrence. Because the global economy depends heavily on Taiwanese-made chips for everything from smartphones to military equipment, any disruption to Taiwan's chip production would have devastating global consequences. This economic interdependence is thought to provide Taiwan with a degree of protection against military aggression.</p>
              <a href="/en/technology/semiconductor-industry" class="read-more">Understand the Silicon Shield &rarr;</a>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary>What is Taiwan's economy based on?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>Taiwan has a highly developed, export-oriented economy — the 21st largest in the world by GDP. Its economy is anchored by the semiconductor and electronics industry, but also includes machinery, petrochemicals, textiles, and an increasingly vibrant services sector. Taiwan underwent an "economic miracle" from the 1960s to 1990s, transforming from an agricultural society to a high-tech powerhouse. Today, it is also known for its thriving startup ecosystem and globally competitive small and medium enterprises.</p>
              <a href="/en/economy/economic-miracle" class="read-more">Read about Taiwan's economic miracle &rarr;</a>
            </div>
          </details>
        </div>

        <!-- Section: Society -->
        <div class="faq-section">
          <h2 class="faq-section-title">Society</h2>

          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary>Is Taiwan a democracy?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>Yes, Taiwan is one of the most vibrant democracies in Asia. After decades of martial law (1949-1987) and authoritarian one-party rule, Taiwan underwent a peaceful democratic transition. It held its first direct presidential election in 1996. Today, Taiwan has a multi-party system with free and fair elections, a free press, an independent judiciary, and strong protections for civil liberties. In 2019, Taiwan became the first place in Asia to legalize same-sex marriage.</p>
              <a href="/en/history/democracy-and-democratization" class="read-more">Learn about Taiwan's democratization &rarr;</a>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary>What is Taiwan's healthcare system like?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>Taiwan's National Health Insurance (NHI), launched in 1995, is a single-payer universal healthcare system that covers over 99% of the population. It provides comprehensive medical services at affordable costs, with most citizens paying low premiums and co-pays. The system is often cited as a model for universal healthcare worldwide, combining high-quality care, short wait times, and advanced medical technology. Taiwan was also recognized globally for its effective public health response during the COVID-19 pandemic.</p>
              <a href="/en/society/human-rights-and-gender-equality" class="read-more">Explore Taiwan's social achievements &rarr;</a>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary>How is Taiwan's education system structured?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>Taiwan has a well-funded public education system with compulsory education from ages 6 to 15 (grades 1-9), followed by three years of senior high school or vocational school. Taiwan has a high university enrollment rate, with top institutions including National Taiwan University (NTU), National Tsing Hua University, and National Cheng Kung University. The country has a strong emphasis on STEM education, which has contributed to its leadership in technology and engineering fields.</p>
              <a href="/en/society/democratic-system" class="read-more">Learn more about Taiwan's society &rarr;</a>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary>What is Taiwan's relationship with China?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>Cross-strait relations between Taiwan and China are complex. The People's Republic of China (PRC) considers Taiwan a breakaway province that must eventually be reunified, while Taiwan has governed itself independently since 1949. The two sides have significant economic ties — China is Taiwan's largest trading partner — but political tensions persist, particularly around issues of sovereignty and international recognition. Taiwan's population increasingly identifies as distinctly Taiwanese rather than Chinese.</p>
              <a href="/en/history/martial-law-era" class="read-more">Understand the historical context &rarr;</a>
            </div>
          </details>
        </div>

      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- CTA Section -->
    <section class="faq-cta">
      <div class="cta-inner">
        <h2>Want to learn more about Taiwan?</h2>
        <p>Taiwan.md is an open-source knowledge base curated to help the world understand Taiwan — its history, culture, economy, and way of life.</p>
        <div class="cta-buttons">
          <a href="/en" class="btn btn-primary">Explore Taiwan.md</a>
          <a href="https://github.com/frank890417/taiwan-md" target="_blank" class="btn btn-outline">Star on GitHub</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

  </div>

